Thulani Gqirana, News24Western Cape ANC secretary Faiez Jacobs (Jenna Etheridge, News24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town &ndash; The ANC Western Cape&rsquo;s provincial secretary, Faiez Jacobs, has been found guilty of assault by the party&rsquo;s national disciplinary committee (NDC).In a statement on Wednesday, NDC chairperson, Derek Hanekom, said Jacobs had been found guilty of fighting with and assaulting&nbsp;former ANC employee, Wesley Seale, at the ANC's provincial offices in&nbsp;November last year.He has been suspended for 18 months.&nbsp;The sanction, however, has been suspended for three years.&ldquo;The NDC took into account that Faiez Jacobs regretted his action and is&nbsp;capable of being rehabilitated,&rdquo; Hanekom said.Expulsion or outright suspension would be too harsh, the party said.Vacate position&ldquo;Consequently, the operation of the 18-month sanction was suspended for a&nbsp;period of three years, subject to the condition that should Faiez Jacobs be found&nbsp;guilty of any&nbsp;act of misconduct specified in the ANC Constitution during the&nbsp;next three years, the 18 month sanction shall become operative and Faiez&nbsp;Jacobs will be required to vacate his position as the provincial secretary of&nbsp;the ANC in the Western Cape,&rdquo; the committee said.Jacobs was first placed on precautionary suspension in December 2015 after being accused of beating up a colleague for failing to write a report on the organisation.The NDC also said the Western Cape ANC should enlist the help of religious groups&nbsp;and professionals in the province to reinforce unity and strengthen&nbsp;governance in the organisation.&nbsp;24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.